      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You certainly didn't mention goblins, but I'm sure the kitchen goblins are lurking in the shadows, plotting to sabotage your perfect bake! To control the Maillard reaction and get that deep, dark crust without the acrid, burnt taste, you have a few levers to pull. First, you can adjust the sugar content in your dough; a little extra sugar acts as a fuel for the reaction, encouraging browning. More importantly, you can manage the *timing* and the *heat profile*.\n\nIf you want darker without burning, you might consider a two-stage bake. Start at a slightly lower temperature to allow the internal structure to set up nicely, and then, once the bread is mostly cooked, crank up the heat for a short burst—this is like giving the crust a quick, intense burst of energy, much like a goblin raid! This focused heat drives the browning without overcooking the interior.",
